Incident.Summary: Recovered vehicle located in marsh area at end of Mount Vernon Road belonging to Yvon Camper (DOB 11-16-1953) who has been missing out of Cambridge, Maryland since 10/15/2023.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: Summary of incident: Black Infinity with MD registration 6DP3312 located at the end of Mount Vernon Road stuck in the marsh belonging to Yvon Camper who was reported missing out of Cambridge, Maryland on 10/16/2023. Scene Processing: Photos were taken of the recovered vehicle and have been attached to this report under attachments. Vehicle was stored at the Maryland State Police, Princess Anne Barrack located in Princess Anne, Maryland. Trooper 4 aviation responded and conducted a search of the area. Trooper 4 was able to capture aerial photos of the entire area around where the vehicle was located. Photos from Trooper 4 have been attached to this report under attachments. Trooper 4 was unable to locate missing person, Yvon Camper. MSP K-9 TFC Graef and his blood hound partner responded in an attempt to locate Yvon Camper however was met with negative results. MSP Dive Team and members of the Mount Vernon Fire Company also responded to search the surrounding water and marsh areas. Narrative: On 10/21/2023 at approximately 1123 hours I, M/T Brown 5545, responded to the end of Mount Vernon Road located in Mount Vernon, Maryland in regard to an abandon vehicle stuck in the marsh. Prior to my arrival it was learned the vehicle was identified by the complainant as a black four door Infinity with Maryland registration 6DP3312 which was registered to reported missing person by the name of Yvon Camper out of Cambridge, Maryland. It was also learned the subject was reported missing on 10/16/2023 from the Cambridge area. A copy of missing person report from Cambridge Police Department was attached to this report in attachments. Upon arrival at the very end of Mount Vernon Road, I made contact with complainant, Daniel Douglas Lewis and his son Charles James Lewis. D. Lewis advised they had been on the property getting ready for duck hunting season when they found the vehicle stuck in the marsh. D. Lewis advised it appeared the vehicle had driven all the way back into the woods then got stuck. D. Lewis advised it appeared the driver then backed the vehicle up and attempted to turn around however backed into a tree breaking the tail light. D. Lewis advised the vehicle then drove out into the marsh and from that point the driver could not get the vehicle out of the marsh. D. Lewis advised they had opened the doors to the vehicle and the keys were still in the vehicle. D. Lewis advised he also opened the trunk of the vehicle to make sure no one was in the trunk. D. Lewis advised there were several ID cards in the driver side door from New York. D. Lewis advised he called the property owner, John Oran Murray and told him about the vehicle being on the property and then called police. D. Lewis advised Murray responded to the scene, and they walked all the way to the end of the peninsula and did not locate anyone. D. Lewis advised Murray left prior to my arrival however could return if needed. At this time, I requested a K-9 with a bloodhound respond to the scene in an attempt to maybe get a good track in an attempt to locate the driver of the vehicle. Aviation was also requested to search the area. Trooper 4 arrived in the area and conducted a search of the marsh and the entire peninsula at the end of Mount Vernon Road however was met with negative results. Trooper 4 was able to capture several aerial photos of the area, and they have been attached to this report under attachments. While Trooper 4 was flying overhead, I was able to take several photos of the vehicle and surrounding area. Inside the vehicle were two New York ID cards and an old Texas ID card all belonging to Yvon Camper. While taking the photos and checking the vehicle, I noticed there was a log inside the driver floorboard as if the driver wedged the gas pedal down. This caused me to believe the driver was attempting to get the vehicle unstuck. There were muddy hand prints on the back trunk area leading me to believe the driver wedged the gas pedal down while trying to push at the same time. The steering wheel was also covered in mud. It was learned Yvon Camper was last on 10/15/2023 wearing a brown suit and there was a brown suit coat located in the vehicle. The gas gauge in the vehicle was reading full. At this time, several units from Special Operation Division (SOD) arrived at the scene and began setting up a command post at the cemetery parking lot of the Asbury United Methodist Church located on the corner of Mount Vernon Road and Pine Beach Road. K-9 TFC Graef and his bloodhound partner arrived on scene and a K-9 search of the area was conducted however met with negative results. After searching the area with TFC Graef and his K-9 partner, members of the MSP Dive Team along with members of the Mount Vernon Fire Departmentarrived on scene and began searching the entire peninsula and surrounding water for any signs of Yvon Camper. A tow was requested to store the vehicle at the barrack and Willies Towing responded to the scene. At this time late shift troopers responded to the scene and Tpr. Brown followed Willies Towing to the barrack with the vehicle to complete a vehicle storage report. At this time, I cleared the scene and SOD continued commanding the search party throughout the evening. On 10/22/2023 I arrived to the barrack and learned SOD was still on scene and the search is still active at this time.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeTitle: Video Surveillance from 25880 Mt. Vernon Road.
IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: The following was captured on body worn camera (BWC). On 10/23/23, I responded to25880 Mt. Vernon Road, Princess Anne, MD to obtain video surveillance. This address is located across the street from the lane whereYvon Campers 2015black Infinity bearing Maryland Registration 6DP3312 was located. I met with the homeowner,Michael Bitzer, 703-431-4455, who advised the following: He has video surveillance that covers the road in front of his residence. The video surveillance is motion activated. Bitzer pulled up his video surveillance from 10/15/23 and I observed the following: 2331 hours: Campers vehicle goes by heading towards the lane where it was located. Campers vehicle is traveling alone, and no other cars are observed in the area. No persons are seen walking to or from the area where the vehicle was located. The video surveillance was reviewed through 10/18/23 and no one was observed leaving the area.

Responding location: Pine Beach Rd Mount Vernon Rd, Princess Anne MD 21853 CC# 23-MSP-036987 Syscom CC# 23-04529 NOTAM: SBY 10/023 Weather CAVU, winds at SBY 8 gusting to 17knots Aircraft: SAR6 Autel Dual Registration: FA3W7TNKRX expiration 3/14/2025 Airspace: Class G RPIC: S/Tpr Smith #5376 Visual Observer: None FAA 107 Certificate number: 4601002 COA: 2022-ESA-10823-COA Flights: 6 Flight Time 1.9 On 10/22/2023 at approximately 0900 hours I was dispatched to the above location for a missing elderly victim. On scene command requested a UAS for aerial search of a large marsh area where the victim was thought to have been. While en route I was diverted to an address in Dorchester County to retrieve a Colorado charger for the UAS in order to increase my on scene flying capability. After retrieval of the equipment I responded to Asbury United Methodist Church where MSP Command Post was set up. Upon arrival, I was advised the subjects vehicle was spotted 2 days ago by a group of hunters. The investigators believed the driver of the vehicle was actually critically missing with a silver alert several days prior. The subject was an elderly male wearing brown clothing who was thought to have left his vehicle on foot after it was disabled in a marsh area. Command gave me a search area from 26390 to 26170 Mount Vernon Rd from the roadway to the shoreline. Syscom was notified and NOTAM established. Due to the approximately mile distance from the Command Post to the search area the UAS was driven to the center search location. A search of the initial area yielded negative results. Command advised the next search area was in the area of 25880 Mount Vernon Rd. NOTAM modified to include the new search area. Upon arrival, it was determined due to the winds it was unsafe to fly the aircraft. SBY reporting 15 gusting to 33 knots. Syscom notified and NOTAM cancelled

On 10/23/23, Destiny Fiddemon (443-754-1552) contacted the Barrack and advised the following: She works at Manokin Manor, nursing home located at 1974 Edgehill Terrace Rd, Princess Anne, MD 21853. She saw Camper at Manokin Manor on the night of10/15/23. Camper was knocking on windows looking for a woman in a white car. She and a co-worker saw him. When he was asked who he was looking Camper could not give a straight answer Camperwas alone and got in a black car and left. Several attempts were made to contact Fiddemon and were meet with negative results.

Reason for Submission: Search Initiated Search Management Search Suspended Narrative: On October 21, 2023, The Maryland State Police Princess Anne Barrack initiated search protocols through the Maryland State Police Special Operations Division [hereinafter referred to as SOD] due to the circumstances related to Yvon Campers [hereinafter referred to as Camper] vehicle being located in Mount Vernon, Maryland. During the initial response, SOD provided search management and an MSP K9 Bloodhound team to conduct an immediate search of the area. The bloodhound track will be captured in (K9 Tracks) system, however yielded negative results. A command post was established at 26566 Mount Vernon Road, (Asbury United Methodist Church and Search Operations were conducted. The search management team utilized the following resources: Maryland State Police Assets: Special Operations K9 Unit Special Operations Search Management Team(s) Underwater Recovery Team Eastern Region Criminal Enforcement Division Aviation (Trooper 4 Trooper 7) UAS Teams Mobile Field Force (Ground Search Teams) margin-left:8px">Princess Anne Barrack Natural Resources Police Assets: Regional Field Officers Search Management Team(s) Waterborne assets margin-left:8px">Aviation assets (Natural 1) Maryland Transportation Authority Police Assets: margin-left:8px">Mobile Field Force (Ground Search Teams) Civilian Resources: Mount Vernon Fire Department Chesapeake Search and Rescue K9 (Air Scent and HRD K9 teams) margin-left:8px">SARDOM Search and Rescue K9 (Air Scent and HRD K9 teams) Based on the multifaceted search of the area conducted, it was decided to suspend search operations as of 1700hrs on Monday, October 23, 2023. The search area will be re-evaluated by the Special Operations Search Management Team and scheduled for a later date if deemed necessary based on weather conditions. Sgt. Lantz, of the Maryland State Police Special Operations Division, briefed Cambridge Police Department of the Search Operation and spoke with the family of Camper. The information gleaned during the investigation conducted by the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division in support of the search for Camper will be forwarded to the Cambridge Police Department to assist with their investigation.

Focus of Supplemental Report: Attempts to locate video surveillance Narrative: On October 21, 2023, I, Corporal Nicholas R. Hager, #6001 of the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division Eastern Region checked the following residences surrounding the Websters Cove Boat Ramp located on Dorsey Road, Princess Anne, Maryland due to the Cambridge Police Department advising they received a ping for Campers cell phone in the area on October 15, 2023: 26548 Harbor Road, Princess Anne, Maryland [No Cameras] Robin Henderson 443-614-1555 26540Harbor Road, Princess Anne, Maryland [No Visible cameras and no answer at door] 26536Harbor Road, Princess Anne, Maryland[No Visible cameras and no answer at door] 26528Harbor Road, Princess Anne, Maryland[No Visible cameras and no answer at door] 26522Harbor Road, Princess Anne, Maryland [Ring camera inoperable] Robbie Thompson 301-399-0867 26520Harbor Road, Princess Anne, Maryland [Camera facing Harbor Road only working during daylight hours] Tom Danisavich 410-845-9324 I was unable to locate any additional visible surveillance cameras in the area.

On 10/23/23, CST K. Patterson, processed Yvon Campers vehicle, a 2015 black Infinity bearing Maryland Registration 6DP3312. Numerous swabs were taken from the vehicle. The swabs taken from the vehicle will be turned over to the Cambridge Police Department, Det. R. Clark, the investigating agency / officer for the missing person report.
The primary investigating agency for the missing person report is The Cambridge Police Department. Any future searches will be documented under this case number. Case closed.

On scene command requested a UAS for aerial search of a large marsh area where the victim was thought to have been. I responded to Asbury United Methodist Church where MSP Command Post was set up. Upon arrival, I was advised the subjects vehicle was spotted 3 days ago by a group of hunters. The investigators believed the driver of the vehicle was actually critically missing with a silver alert several days prior. The subject was an elderly male wearing brown clothing who was thought to have left his vehicle on foot after it was disabled in a marsh area. Command gave me a search area from 25880 Mount Vernon Rd from the roadway to the shoreline. Syscom was notified and NOTAM established. Due to the approximately mile distance from the Command Post to the search area the UAS was driven to the center search location. A search of the initial area yielded negative results. During the search to ensure area was toughly searched a pre-planned drone flight was conducted to allow for photographs to be taken of the area, which were later reviewed to ensure nothing was missed or overlooked. The photographs have been uploaded to Veripic per MSP policy. Command advised the next search area was in the area of 25880 Mount Vernon Rd back to the Command Post checking both sides of the roadway approximately 50 feet off the road. The search of the new area also yielded negative results. Upon arrival back at Command Post search operations were concluding and myself and Cpl. Dungee were released. Syscom was notified card and NOTAM were closed.

Reason for Submission: Grid Search Conducted Narrative: On Thursday, November 9, 2023, The Maryland State Police Special Operations Division conducted a large-scale ground and air search in the area of Mount Vernon, Maryland in an attempt to locate Yvon Camper with negative results. The following resources were utilized during the search: Maryland State Police Resources: Special Operations Division Search Management Team Mobile Field Force SAR Technicians Criminal Enforcement Division Eastern Region Underwater Recovery Team margin-left:8px">Crash Team UAS Maryland Department of Transportation: margin-left:8px">Mobile Field Force SAR Technicians Maryland Natural Resources Police: margin-left:8px">Aviation Assets Natural One Mount Vernon Fire Department: margin-left:8px">Argo Chesapeake Search and Rescue: Ground Search Teams margin-left:8px">Air Scent and HRD K9 Teams I met with Cambridge Police Department Detective Clark at the command post and provided her with all current and up-to-date information. Reason for Submission: Flashlight located Narrative: On November 14, 2023, John Barnette from the Mount Vernon Fire Department [hereinafter referred to as Barnette] contacted the Maryland State Police Princess Anne Barrack in regard to locating a flashlight. I met with Barnette at the Mount Vernon Fire Department, and he provided a red plastic flashlight that he found at approximately 0800hrs while conducting his own search in the area of grid coordinate 38.23239, -75.85644. I observed the flashlight to be red, plastic, and not operational. The flashlight was collected from Barnette and transported to the Maryland State Police Princess Anne Barrack where it was packaged and placed in the Princess Anne Barrack Temp Storage area and will be transferred to Cambridge Police Department. Case remains Closed.

November 09, 2023 I was requested to utilize a sUAS to support search and rescue operations in the area of 26586 Mount Vernon Road in Princess Anne, Somerset County, Maryland. The MSP was conducting a large area search for a missing person, identified as Yvon Camper, from Cambridge, Maryland. The sUAS operation was conducted in the Class G airspace. A Notice to Airman (NOTAM) was filed, number SBY 11/007. The sUAS operation was completed using MSP sUAS Crash Recon 6 (FA3M7N734E, Autel EVO2 Dual). The flights were conducted utilizing the MSP Tactical Beyond Visual Line of Sight Waiver. Four (4) flights were conducted for a total time of eighty-five (85) minutes. There was no damage to any MSP equipment. The search was negative.
